The paper focuses on developing a multimodal interaction framework for a human rescuer to operate with co-located drones during search and rescue missions. This involves designing a system that supports effective and natural mixed-initiative interaction between the human and the robots. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of a mixed ground and aerial robotic platform, which falls under the Robotics (cs.RO) category. The development of the interaction framework also involves the use of artificial intelligence techniques, which could place the paper under the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) category. The paper also discusses the use of a simulated case study, which could fall under the Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA) category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of a system to support search and rescue activities, which could fall under the Systems and Control (cs.SY) category.
